{{Infobox museum |name = Archaeological Museum of Ostia |native_name = ''Museo Archeologico Ostiense'' |native_name_lang = it |image = Ostia_Antica_Museo.jpg |imagesize = 280 |map_type = Italy Lazio |map_caption = Location in Lazio |caption = Archaeological Museum of Ostia |coordinates = {{coord|41.75559|12.28764|type:landmark_region:IT|display=inline}} |established = |dissolved = |location = Viale dei Romagnoli, 717 [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]], [[Italy]] |type = [[archaeology]] |visitors = |director = |curator = |publictransit = |website = }} The '''Museo Archeologico Ostiense''' (or ''Archaeological Museum of Ostia'') is an [[archaeological museum]] dedicated to the ancient Roman city of [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]] in [[Rome]], [[Italy]].
The museum was built by [[Pope Pius IX]], who in 1865 had to readapt a fifteenth-century building used as a store to create a city museum. Contained in the museum are numerous archaeological objects which came to light during a long period of excavations. The collection includes, for example, a collection of portraits of famous people from ancient Ostia, including [[philosopher]]s and members of the royal family, such as busts depicting [[Asclepius]] and Volcacius Myropnous,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ostia-antica.org/valkvisuals/html/tombe_07.htm|title=tombe 7|work=ostia-antica.org}}</ref> a portrait of [[Faustina the Elder]] and the head of [[Trajan]]. The museum also has a large collection of sculptures, including the statue of [[Perseus]] holding the head of [[Medusa]], the sculptural group of [[Mithraic mysteries|Mithras]] slaying the bull, and other works. There are other examples on display of great interest, such as small groups in marble depicting [[Cupid and Psyche]] and other subjects, and in another section of the museum, [[sarcophagus|sarcophagi]] and [[relief]]s. On display are also examples of wall paintings from different burials and emblems of [[polychrome]] [[mosaic]]s, such as the [[Christ Blessing (Raphael)|Christ Blessing]]. These works of great historical and artistic value, are then supported by a collection of minor works such as crafts, glass, and even teaches some at the shop, and some interesting facts, such as the marble slab found in the temple of the goddess of war, [[Bellona (goddess)|Bellona]], on which are carved two pairs of feet opposite, probably a [[Votive offering|votive]] object.<ref>[http://www.musei.it/lazio/roma/museo-archeologico-ostiense.asp Museo Archeologico Ostiense di Roma] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207024020/http://www.musei.it/lazio/roma/museo-archeologico-ostiense.asp |date=2013-12-07 }}, Retrieved 18 October 2012</ref> {| |[[File:Ostia Antica - museo 1050467.JPG|thumb|Roman copy of a winged goddess from the Temple of Jupiter in Ostia Antica.]] |[[File:Ostia Antica - museo 1050468.JPG|thumb|A female statue and male busts in the Archaeological Museum of Ostia.]] |} ==See also== * [[Ostia Antica]]
